    body: "About 2.5 million households in the United States are headed by grandparents who are the main caregivers for one or more grandchildren. Many of these families came together suddenly, after a parent's death, a deployment, a hospitalization, an arrest, or a court removal. Whatever the reason, one of the first big hurdles that lands on a grandparent's kitchen table is school enrollment. The local public school has a stack of forms, the office staff wants documents you may not have, and the start of the school year is bearing down. This guide walks through what schools usually ask for, where to find each document, and what to do when something is missing.\n\nFederal law is firmly on your side. The McKinney-Vento Homeless Assistance Act and a 2008 federal law called the Fostering Connections to Success and Increasing Adoptions Act both require public schools to enroll a child in your care right away, even if some paperwork is missing. Every state has also passed a kinship caregiver or educational consent law that lets a grandparent enroll a grandchild in school without going to court first. The school cannot turn the child away because you do not have a custody order, an immunization record, or a birth certificate the day you walk in. The school must enroll the child first and help you gather the documents over the following thirty days.\n\nThat said, the smoother your paperwork, the smoother the school year. Most schools want six basic things: proof the child lives at your address, proof of the child's age, a record of past schools attended, immunization records, an emergency contact form, and some form of caregiver authorization that says you are the adult in charge. You can pull most of these together in a week with a few phone calls and a couple of car trips. None of it requires a lawyer for the first step, although a lawyer may be needed later for full legal guardianship covered in a separate guide.\n\nBefore you begin, set aside a binder or a folder labeled with the child's name. Inside the folder, keep a copy of every document you collect, along with a list of phone numbers for the previous school, the child's doctor, and the local Department of Health birth records office. Have a working printer at home or know where the nearest public library or senior center printing service is. Most school districts now accept digital scans through an email attachment or a parent portal, so a smartphone camera can stand in for a scanner if needed. Plan for the whole process to take about two weeks, although the school must enroll the child within five days of you asking.",
